@${K} is a field, @${F} is a subfield of @${K}.

If @${a \in K} is the root of a polynomial of @${F[x]}, then @${\alpha} is algebraic over @${F}.

@${\mathbb{R} = K, \mathbb{Q} = F}.

Consider @${\alpha = \sqrt{5 + \sqrt[3]{6}} \in \mathbb{R}} is algebraic over @${\mathbb{Q}} since it is a root of a polynomial in @${\mathbb{Q}[x]}

@example{
          @${x - \sqrt{5 + \sqrt[3]{6}}}

          @${\alpha} is a root. It is in @${\mathbb{R}[x]}, but @bold{not} in @${\mathbb{Q}}

          @$${x - \sqrt{5 + \sqrt[3]{6}} = 0}
          @$${x = \sqrt{5 + \sqrt[3]{6}}}
          @$${x^{2} = 5 + \sqrt[3]{6}}
          @$${x^{2} - 5 = \sqrt[3]{6}}
          @$${(x^{2} - 5)^{3} = 6}

          @${\alpha} is a root of @${x^6 - 15x^4 + 75x^2 - 131 = 0 \in \mathbb{Q}[x]}
}

Any element in @${K} that is not algebraic over @${F} is @italic{transcendental} over @${F}. e.g. @${\pi}, @${e}, @${0.101001000100001\ldots}

The set of algebraic numbers over @${\mathbb{Q}} is countable.

@$${|\mathbb{Q}| = |\mathbb{N}|}
@$${|\mathbb{R}| > |\mathbb{N}|}
The cardinality of the set of transcendental numbers @${> |\mathbb{N}|}

@centered{@${\alpha \in K} s.t. @${\alpha} is algebraic over @${F}.}
@${\alpha} is a root of the polynomial in @${F[x]}

The @italic{minimal polynomial} of @${\alpha} over @${F} is a monic, irreducible polynomial @${f(x) \in F[x]} s.t. @${\alpha} is a root of @${f}

@margin-note{@bold{monadic} the leading coefficient of the polynomial is 1}.

If @${a \in K} is algebraic over @${F}, then the minimal polynomial of @${\alpha} over @${F} is unique.
@proof{
          Let @${f(x), g(x)} be minimal polynomials. Assume @${g(x)} has the lowest degree among all minimum polynomials.
          If @${\deg f \neq \deg g}, without loss of generality, let @${\deg f > \deg g}
          @$${f(x) = q(x)g(x) + r(x), \deg r < \deg g}

          If @${r(x) \neq 0}, then it contradicts the fact that g has the lowest degree among all minimal polynomials.

          If @${r(x) = 0}, then @${f(x)} is not irreducible (contradiction)

          If @${\deg f = \deg g} then @${f(x) - g(x)} has a degree less than degree g.

          If @${f(x) - g(x) = 0} then since @${f(\alpha) - g(\alpha) = 0}.

          This contradicts that @${g} has the lowest degree.

          @${\therefore f(x) - g(x) = 0} i.e @${f(x) = g(x)} @${\therefore} the minimal polynomial is unique.
}

@example{
          @${\sqrt[3]{6}} satisfies @${4x^{3} - 24} @${\rightarrow} @${x^{3} - 6} is irreducible,
          so the minimal polynomial @${(x^{6} - 36) = (x^{3} - 6)(x^{3} + 6)} is not irreducible.
}

Any polynomial that @${\alpha} satisfies is a multiple of the minimal polynomial.

Let @${F} be a finite field.

Consider @${1, 1 + 1, 1 + 1 + 1, \underbrace{1 + \ldots + 1}_{n} = 0}

@${n} is referred to as the characteristic.

This @${n} is a prime.
@proof{
          Assume @${n = k * l}, @${k, l \neq 1}

          @${\underbrace{(1 + 1 + \ldots + 1)}_{l}\underbrace{(1 + 1 + \ldots + 1)}_{k}}

          But the first object is a zero divisor! @${\therefore} contradiction.
}

Now @${\{0, 1, 1 + 1, \ldots, \underbrace{1 + \ldots + 1}_{p - 1}\} \cong \mathbb{Z}p}

We can think of @${F} as an extension of @${\mathbb{Z}p}

Recall that @${F} is a vector space over @${\mathbb{Z}p}

Let the basis be @${\{b_{1}, \ldots, b_{m}\}}

@(define blank "\\underline{\\hspace{3mm}}")

@${F = \{@blank b_{1} + @blank b_{2} + \ldots + @blank b_{m} : @blank \in \mathbb{Z}p\}}

Since each @${b_i} has @${p} choices, the size of the set is @${\underbrace{p * p * \ldots * p}_{m}} @${\Rightarrow} @${|F| = p^m}

